ct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nGiven an m x n binary matrix mat, return the distance of the nearest 0 for each cell.\nThe distance between two cells sharing a common edge is 1.\n \nExample 1:\n\n\nInput: mat = [[0,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,0]]\nOutput: [[0,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,0]]\n\nExample 2:\n\n\nInput: mat = [[0,0,0],[0,1,0],[1,1,1]]\nOutput: [[0,0,0],[0,1,0],[1,2,1]]\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nm == mat.length\nn == mat[i].length\n1 <= m, n <= 104\n1 <= m * n <= 104\nmat[i][j] is either 0 or 1.\nThere is at least one 0 in mat.\n\n \nNote: This question is the same as 1765: https://leetcode.com/problems/map-of-highest-peak/\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def updateMatrix(self, mat: List[List[int]]) -> List[List[int]]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve this problem, we can use a Breadth-First Search (BFS) approach. The idea is to start from all the cells that contain `0` and then propagate the distances to the neighboring cells. This way, each cell will be updated with the shortest distance to the nearest `0`.\n\nHere's the step-by-step plan:\n1. Initialize a queue and add all the positions of `0`s in the matrix to this queue.\n2. Initialize a result matrix `dist` of the same size as `mat` with all values set to `-1` (indicating unvisited cells). Set the distance for all `0`s to `0` as they are already at distance `0` from themselves.\n3. Perform BFS from all the `0`s simultaneously. For each cell, check its neighbors. If a neighbor has not been visited yet (i.e., its distance is `-1`), update its distance and add it to the queue.\n4. Continue this process until the queue is empty, ensuring all cells have been processed.\n\nHere is the implementation:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def updateMatrix(self, mat: List[List[int]]) -> List[List[int]]:\n        m, n = len(mat), len(mat[0])\n        # Initialize the distance matrix with -1\n        dist = [[-1] * n for _ in range(m)]\n        # Initialize the queue with all positions of 0s\n        queue = deque()\n        \n        for r in range(m):\n            for c in range(n):\n                if mat[r][c] == 0:\n                    queue.append((r, c))\n                    dist[r][c] = 0\n        \n        # Directions for moving up, down, left, right\n        directions = [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]\n        \n        # Perform BFS\n        while queue:\n            r, c = queue.popleft()\n            for dr, dc in directions:\n                nr, nc = r + dr, c + dc\n                if 0 <= nr < m and 0 <= nc < n and dist[nr][nc] == -1:\n                    dist[nr][nc] = dist[r][c] + 1\n                    queue.append((nr, nc))\n        \n        return dist\n```\n\nThis solution ensures that each cell is processed in the shortest path order, resulting in the correct distances to the nearest `0` for each cell. The time complexity is O(m * n) since each cell is added to the queue at most once, and the space complexity is also O(m * n) due to the distance matrix and the queue.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}